<Base
  title="Research | Alfie McGlennon"
  description="Compound heat stress risk modelling across Europe. Copula-based multiplicative decomposition of climate-model bias, with XGBoost predicting Kendall's tau dependence from atmospheric circulation patterns."
  ogTitle="Research | Alfie McGlennon"
  ogDescription="Compound heat stress, copula methods, and ML for dependence correction in climate models."
>
  <article class="page-narrow research">
    <p class="kicker">Dissertation</p>
    <h1>Predicting compound heat stress risk across Europe</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      A copula-based framework for diagnosing where climate-model bias in
      compound extremes actually comes from, and using machine learning to
      correct the dependence structure directly.
    </p>

    <p>
      Climate models simulate compound extremes badly. A heatwave with high
      humidity, a drought followed by intense rainfall, a wind storm
      coinciding with a storm surge: these are the events that drive real
      impacts. They are also where global climate models tend to disagree
      most strongly with reality. Most existing bias correction methods
      treat variables one at a time, which fixes each marginal distribution
      but leaves the joint dependence structure untouched. If you
      bias-correct temperature and humidity separately, you get a corrected
      climatology for each, and a compound heat-stress climatology that
      may still be wrong.
    </p>

    <h2>The decomposition</h2>
    <p>
      My dissertation develops a multiplicative decomposition of compound
      hazard bias:
    </p>
    <pre><code>M_total = M_marginal &times; M_dependence</code></pre>
    <p>
      This splits compound bias into two diagnostic components.
      <strong>M_marginal</strong> captures the bias you would see if the
      dependence structure were correctly modelled and only the marginals
      were wrong. <strong>M_dependence</strong> captures the bias that
      remains after the marginals are corrected, attributable purely to
      dependence-structure error. The two multiply together to recover the
      full compound bias. Once decomposed, you can see which component
      dominates in which region and at which return period. That alone
      changes which method you reach for to correct it.
    </p>

    <h2>Copulas, briefly</h2>
    <p>
      The decomposition is built on copulas. A copula is a function that
      fully captures the dependence between variables, completely separated
      from their individual distributions. The mathematical foundation is
      Sklar&rsquo;s theorem from 1959: every multivariate distribution can
      be written as its marginal distributions composed with a copula that
      encodes their dependence. You fit the marginals to your data, fit the
      copula to your data, and the two can be modified independently.
      Climate models can have correct dependence with biased marginals, or
      vice versa. Marginal bias correction without addressing the copula
      leaves the dependence error in place, and on compound extremes that
      is exactly the error that matters.
    </p>

    <h2>ML for dependence</h2>
    <p>
      The new part is the ML-driven dependence correction. I train XGBoost
      to predict Kendall&rsquo;s tau, the rank-based dependence statistic,
      from large-scale atmospheric circulation patterns. The features are
      circulation modes from ERA5 reanalysis: geopotential height fields,
      mean sea-level pressure, jet-stream position indices. The label is
      the local Kendall&rsquo;s tau between temperature and specific
      humidity, computed for each grid cell on a rolling window. If
      circulation patterns shape dependence, and we can learn that mapping,
      we can predict the dependence structure under CMIP6 projections
      directly, rather than assuming it from a fitted copula. This is a
      different kind of climate-model-aware ML: not predicting the
      meteorological field itself, but predicting how its variables
      co-vary.
    </p>

    <h2>Data and validation</h2>
    <p>
      The dataset stack is ERA5 reanalysis as the ground-truth dependence
      climatology over 1981 to 2020, CMIP6 projections for the historical
      and future scenarios, and Destination Earth digital-twin output where
      it overlaps. Validation works at two levels. First, can the
      M_marginal versus M_dependence decomposition reproduce known compound
      biases when applied to CMIP6 evaluated against ERA5? Second, does the
      XGBoost dependence predictor generalise out of sample, both
      geographically and across different models?
    </p>

    <h2>Publication plan</h2>
    <p>
      Two papers are emerging from this. The methods paper on the
      multiplicative decomposition targets a traditional extremes or
      statistical climatology journal. The ML-driven dependence paper
      targets the Royal Meteorological Society&rsquo;s special issue on
      <em>Advances in Machine Learning for Weather and Climate</em>, with a
      December 2026 deadline.
    </p>

    <hr class="research-rule" />

